<span id = "attack_help">&nbsp;</span>
<div class= "help">
  <h3>Attack</h3>
  <p> Enter the attack bonus of this attack, and select the damage dice up to 2d20, and the total damage bonus for the attack.
      Also select the appropriate critical threat range (the natural dice rolls that yield a critical threat with than weapon e.g. 20, or 19 to 20)
      and critical hit multiplier (the number of times the normal number of damage dice is multiplied and the number of times the damage dice are multiplied).
  </p>
  <p> Note that for criticals, the critical threat is not a guaranteed critical. A second roll must be made and that must be a hit with the same attack stats for it
      to be a critical hit rather than a normal hit. So if the opponent's AC is so high that a natural 20 is required to hit, then a critical hit would require two
      natural 20s in a row!
  </p>
  <p> Note also that when calculating critical hit damage, the total damage on damage dice plus bonus dice is not simply doubled for x2 multiplier or tripled for x3 multiplier, etc.
      Instead the number of damage dice rolled is doubled or tripled, and then added to double or triple the damage bonus. So if the damage dice is normally 2d6 + 5,
      roll 4d6 and add 10 for total damage. This has the effect of evening out critical damage closer to its mean value.
  </p>
  <p> To add stats for another attack in the same round, click the "Add Attack" button, and to remove the most recently added attack, click the "Remove Attack" button.
  </p>

  <div class= "bottom">
    <%= link_to "Return",'javascript:history.go(-1);', class: 'btn btn-primary navbar-btn' %>
  </div>
</div>

<span id = "opponent_help">&nbsp;</span>
<div class= "help">
  <h3>Opponent</h3>
  <p> Enter the opponent's Armour Class (AC) and any Damage Reduction for that attack. Damage Reduction has a complicated effect on calculating damage per round
      so that it is not possible simply to take mean damage on damage rolls. If the damage reduction is greater than the attack's damage bonus, the attack may do zero damage but
      never negative damage; to do any damage now is a less than 100% probability even with a hit, a probability that varies according to the relative sizes of the damage reduction
      and attack damage bonus.
  </p>
  <p> Some opponents will be immune to critical hits. This will obviously reduce the Damage per Round (DPR), more so for lower opponent armour classes where it is more likely to
      score a critical hit when there is a critical threat.
  </p>

  <div class= "bottom">
    <%= link_to "Return",'javascript:history.go(-1);', class: 'btn btn-primary navbar-btn' %>
  </div>
</div>

<span id = "calculate_round_help">&nbsp;</span>
<div class= "help">
  <h3>Calculate Round</h3>
  <p> Clicking this button calculates the total mean Damage per Round (DPR) for all the attacks entered. If the user is logged in, a table of DPR for all Armour Class (AC)
      values is saved to the user's profile.
  </p>

  <div class= "bottom">
    <%= link_to "Return",'javascript:history.go(-1);', class: 'btn btn-primary navbar-btn' %>
  </div>
</div>

<span id = "export_table_help">&nbsp;</span>
<div class= "help">
  <h3>Export Table</h3>
  <p> When the user is not logged in, clicking this button from the calculations page downloads an Excel worksheet file with a table
      of Damage per Round (DPR) values for all Armour Class (AC) values, not just the entered AC value.
  </p>

  <div class= "bottom">
    <%= link_to "Return",'javascript:history.go(-1);', class: 'btn btn-primary navbar-btn' %>
  </div>
</div>

<span id = "download_help">&nbsp;</span>
<div class= "help">
  <h3>Download File</h3>
  <p> When the user is logged in, clicking this button from the Show Rounds page downloads an Excel worksheet file with a table
      of all the saved rounds, with attack and opponent stats and Damage per Round (DPR) vs Armour Class (AC) tables.
  </p>
  <p> This is also graphically represented, so the user can instantly min-max different attack strategies for different opponent AC values.
      For example, at a point where one round's DPR crossed above the value of another round's, it would be at this range of AC values where
      that strategy should be used. Now you know when to use flurry, or whether to attack with two weapons or one!
  </p>

  <div class= "bottom">
    <%= link_to "Return",'javascript:history.go(-1);', class: 'btn btn-primary navbar-btn' %>
  </div>
</div>

<span id = "show_rounds_help">&nbsp;</span>
<div class= "help">
  <h3>Show Rounds</h3>
  <p> When the user is logged in, clicking this button from the calculations page brings up a page listing, most recent uppermost, all the saved rounds and their attack
      and opponent stats and the associated Damage per Round (DPR) vs Armour Class (AC) tables.
  </p>

  <div class= "bottom">
    <%= link_to "Return",'javascript:history.go(-1);', class: 'btn btn-primary navbar-btn' %>
  </div>
</div>

<span id = "exit_help">&nbsp;</span>
<div class= "help">
  <h3>Reset and Exit</h3>
  <p> Clicking this button will reset the session's values for attacks and opponent stats and return to the home screen.
  </p>
  <p> When the user is logged in, it will also permanently delete <i>all</i> the saved rounds of Damage per Round (DPR) vs Armour Class (AC) tables for the current user.
  </p>

  <div class= "bottom">
    <%= link_to "Return",'javascript:history.go(-1);', class: 'btn btn-primary navbar-btn' %>
  </div>
</div>

